{"title_page": "Mahua (snack)", "text_new": "{{Infobox food\n| name             = Mahua\n| image            = Mafaimage2.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Mahua with tea\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[China]], [[Panama]] \n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Doughnut]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Dough]], [[peanut oil]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Mahua''' (\u9ebb\u82b1) or Fried Dough Twist is a Chinese [[dough]] twist that is fried in [[peanut oil]]. It has a shiny and golden look. It is prepared in various ways with different flavors, which range from sweet to spicy, and usually has a dense and crisp texture. The origin of Mahua could be traced back thousands of years ago. Many places have the tradition of eating Mahua, and Mahua is considered a signature food of the northern Chinese city of [[Tianjin]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ichongqing.info/culture/chongqing-local-food/mahua-fried-dough-twist/|title=Mahua (Fried Dough Twist)|last=Martini|website=iChongqing|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theworldofchinese.com/2016/02/mahua-the-tianjin-treat/|title=Mahua: the Tianjin Treat|date=2016-02-16|website=The World of Chinese|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Origin ==\nAccording to legend, Mahua originated 2000 years ago. At that time, people celebrated a three-day festival in which they were not allowed to use fire. The lack of access to fire meant that people were unable to cook during the festival. In order to eat, people needed to prepare food that did not spoil easily, before the festival. Thus, the original form of Mahua, which is fried dough with honey, was invented. Because the original Mahua could be kept fresh for a long time, it was a good snack for the festival.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn another tale of the origin of Mahua, Mahua was created to curse the hateful scorpion. At that time, the wild scorpions were bothering people. For revenge, people twisted wheat dough into the shape of the scorpion's tail, then fried and ate it.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Tianjin Guifaxiang 18th Street Mahua ==\nThe most famous Mahua brand is \"Guifaxiang 18th Street Fried Dough Twists\" from [[Tianjin]], because the shop originated from the 18th Street of the old town. In Tianjin, people normally eat Mahua which have sweet or salty flavor. The most common ingredients used in Tianjin Mahua are flour, sesame, walnut, peanuts and sweet-scented [[osmanthus]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306150023/http://english.cri.cn/6566/2009/09/28/902s519141.htm\n|title=18th Street Fried Dough Twists|author1=|date=2009-09-28}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/food/2017-05/08/content_29251771.htm|title=Tasting Tianjin with its signature foods[1]- Chinadaily.com.cn|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\nThe Guifaxiang Mahua store was founded on the western side of Tianjin's [[Hai River|Haihe River]] in 1927 by Laoba Liu. The name of \"Guifaxiang\" implies the meaning of \"sweet-scented osmanthus' seeds' aroma, be diligent and be lucky\"(\u6842\u5b50\u98d8\u9999\uff0c\u53d1\u6124\u56fe\u5f3a\uff0c\u5409\u7965\u5982\u610f). Because the store is on the 18th Street, the Mahua is called \"Guifaxiang 18th Street Mahua\". The owner Laoba was a talented baker and he had invented a way to put assorted fillings into the Mahua to improve its appearance and taste. All people loved the snack. gradually, \"Guifaxiang 18th street Mahua\" had become one of the most famous snacks of Tianjin and it became famous around the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gfx.com.cn/|title=\u6842\u53d1\u7965{{!}}\u4e2d\u534e\u8001\u5b57\u53f7 \u5929\u6d25\u6842\u53d1\u7965\u5341\u516b\u8857\u9ebb\u82b1\u98df\u54c1\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|website=www.gfx.com.cn|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\nThe company \"Guifaxiang\" has built a Museum of Mahua for visitors to learn about the history of Mahua and tour the factory line.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n<br />\n[[File:18th_Street_Mahua.jpg|thumb|Photo of Mahua from Guifaxiang 18th Street.]]\n\n== Chen-Mahua in Chongqing ==\nChen-Mahua is a kind of Mahua that is famous in [[Chongqing]] and has been popular in Chongqing since the [[Qing dynasty|Qing Dynasty]]. It is originated in [[Ciqikou, Chongqing|Ciqikou]]. Chen-Mahua is normally made in ten flavors, which are original taste, [[Sesame|black sesame]], pepper salt, black rice, corn, rock sugar glutinous rice, spicy, seaweed, chocolate, and honey. The spicy flavor Mahua is a signature Mahua of Chongqing.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n== Mahua in Panama ==\nThe snack is extremely popular in [[Panama]], where it has been adopted as a national dish and is referred to as ''maf\u00e1''.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iLBVDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=panamanian+mafa#v=onepage&q=panamanian%20mafa&f=false|title=Panamanian Spanish: Speak like a Native!, by Lee Jamison|date=2019-02-14|last1=Jamison|first1=Lee}}</ref> It was brought over by [[Ethnic Chinese in Panama|Chinese immigrants]] during the nineteenth century.\n\nThere is also a savory variant which is green and gets its flavor and color from powdered algae.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Twisted doughnut]]\n* [[List of doughnut varieties]]\n* [[List of fried dough varieties]]   \n*{{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mahua (food)}}\n* [http://wtanaka.com/node/7827?k=China Ma Hua]\n* [http://english.cri.cn/6566/2009/09/28/902s519141.htm]\n{{Doughnuts}}\n\n[[Category:Doughnuts]]\n[[Category:Chinese desserts]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox food\n| name             = Mahua\n| image            = Mafaimage2.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          = Mahua with tea\n| alternate_name   = \n| country          = [[China]], [[Panama]] \n| region           = \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| type             = [[Doughnut]]\n| served           = \n| main_ingredient  = [[Dough]], [[peanut oil]]\n| variations       = \n| calories         = \n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''Mahua''' (\u9ebb\u82b1) or Fried Dough Twist is a Chinese [[dough]] twist that is fried in [[peanut oil]]. It has a shiny and golden look. It is prepared in various ways with different flavors, which range from sweet to spicy, and usually has a dense and crisp texture. The origin of Mahua could be traced back thousands of years ago. Many places have the tradition of eating Mahua, and Mahua is considered a signature food of the northern Chinese city of [[Tianjin]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ichongqing.info/culture/chongqing-local-food/mahua-fried-dough-twist/|title=Mahua (Fried Dough Twist)|last=Martini|website=iChongqing|language=en|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theworldofchinese.com/2016/02/mahua-the-tianjin-treat/|title=Mahua: the Tianjin Treat|date=2016-02-16|website=The World of Chinese|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\n== Origin ==\nAccording to legend, Mahua originated 2000 years ago. At that time, people celebrated a three-day festival in which they were not allowed to use fire. The lack of access to fire meant that people were unable to cook during the festival. In order to eat, people needed to prepare food that did not spoil easily, before the festival. Thus, the original form of Mahua, which is fried dough with honey, was invented. Because the original Mahua could be kept fresh for a long time, it was a good snack for the festival.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn another tale of the origin of Mahua, Mahua was created to curse the hateful scorpion. At that time, the wild scorpions were bothering people. For revenge, people twisted wheat dough into the shape of the scorpion's tail, then fried and ate it.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Tianjin Guifaxiang 18th Street Mahua ==\nThe most famous Mahua brand is \"Guifaxiang 18th Street Fried Dough Twists\" from [[Tianjin]], because the shop originated from the 18th Street of the old town. In Tianjin, people normally eat Mahua which have sweet or salty flavor. The most common ingredients used in Tianjin Mahua are flour, sesame, walnut, peanuts and sweet-scented [[osmanthus]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306150023/http://english.cri.cn/6566/2009/09/28/902s519141.htm\n|title=18th Street Fried Dough Twists|author1=|date=2009-09-28}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.chinadaily.com.cn/food/2017-05/08/content_29251771.htm|title=Tasting Tianjin with its signature foods[1]- Chinadaily.com.cn|website=www.chinadaily.com.cn|access-date=2020-01-31}}</ref>\n\nThe Guifaxiang Mahua store was founded on the western side of Tianjin's [[Hai River|Haihe River]] in 1927 by Laoba Liu. The name of \"Guifaxiang\" implies the meaning of \"sweet-scented osmanthus' seeds' aroma, be diligent and be lucky\"(\u6842\u5b50\u98d8\u9999\uff0c\u53d1\u6124\u56fe\u5f3a\uff0c\u5409\u7965\u5982\u610f). Because the store is on the 18th Street, the Mahua is called \"Guifaxiang 18th Street Mahua\". The owner Laoba was a talented baker and he had invented a way to put assorted fillings into the Mahua to improve its appearance and taste. All people loved the snack. gradually, \"Guifaxiang 18th street Mahua\" had become one of the most famous snacks of Tianjin and it became famous around the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gfx.com.cn/|title=\u6842\u53d1\u7965{{!}}\u4e2d\u534e\u8001\u5b57\u53f7 \u5929\u6d25\u6842\u53d1\u7965\u5341\u516b\u8857\u9ebb\u82b1\u98df\u54c1\u80a1\u4efd\u6709\u9650\u516c\u53f8|website=www.gfx.com.cn|access-date=2020-02-09}}</ref>\n\nThe company \"Guifaxiang\" has built a Museum of Mahua for visitors to learn about the history of Mahua and tour the factory line.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n<br />\n[[File:18th_Street_Mahua.jpg|thumb|Photo of Mahua from Guifaxiang 18th Street.]]\n\n== Chen-Mahua in Chongqing ==\nChen-Mahua is a kind of Mahua that is famous in [[Chongqing]] and has been popular in Chongqing since the [[Qing dynasty|Qing Dynasty]]. It is originated in [[Ciqikou, Chongqing|Ciqikou]]. Chen-Mahua is normally made in ten flavors, which are original taste, [[Sesame|black sesame]], pepper salt, black rice, corn, rock sugar glutinous rice, spicy, seaweed, chocolate, and honey. The spicy flavor Mahua is a signature Mahua of Chongqing.<ref name=\":2\"/>\n\n== Mahua in Panama ==\nThe snack is extremely popular in [[Panama]], where it has been adopted as a national dish and is referred to as ''maf\u00e1''.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/?id=iLBVDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA81&lpg=PA81&dq=panamanian+mafa#v=onepage&q=panamanian%20mafa&f=false|title=Panamanian Spanish: Speak like a Native!, by Lee Jamison|date=2019-02-14|last1=Jamison|first1=Lee}}</ref> It was brought over by Chinese immigrants during the nineteenth century.\n\nThere is also a savory variant which is green and gets its flavor and color from powdered algae.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Twisted doughnut]]\n* [[List of doughnut varieties]]\n* [[List of fried dough varieties]]   \n*{{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Mahua (food)}}\n* [http://wtanaka.com/node/7827?k=China Ma Hua]\n* [http://english.cri.cn/6566/2009/09/28/902s519141.htm]\n{{Doughnuts}}\n\n[[Category:Doughnuts]]\n[[Category:Chinese desserts]]\n", "name_user": "Bambi'nin annesi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMahua in Panama:internal link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mahua_(snack)"}
